  "texts": [
    "Applying the product rule and the linearity in Ψ in the definition (5.7) of F Ψ (z),F η + ∂ξ + (z) = ∂F J + (z) -F ∂η + ξ + (z).Again, the second term will vanish at z * a, leaving 33F ∂ΦJ + (z * a) = F η + ∂ξ + (z * a) = ∂F J + (z * a).",
    "It then follows that, as z → z * a, F ∂ΦJ + (z) = F ∂Φ (z)F J + (z) = F ∂Φ (z) (z -z * a)∂F J + (z * a) + O((z -z * a) 2) = F ∂Φ (z) (z -z * a)F ∂ΦJ + (z * a) + O((z -z * a) 2).",
    "32 In fact, the arguments of appendix E can simply be applied to this case to show an analogous factorisationF U J + (z) = F U (z)F J + (z)from which the zeroes at z ∈ {z * a, t k } trivially follow.",
    "33 If z * a is a higher order zero of F J + (z), then of course ∂F J + (z * a) = 0.",
    "However, in the following we could account for this by simply expanding in a Taylor series as z → z * a to find the first non-zero contribution."
